This set of interaction graphs of a cross-interface connection like the connection between definitions/requirements can be on a different layer than the most useful or most basic definition/requirement graph given the large number of these interaction graphs for each cross-interface connection.
Different axes like optimization/abstraction/interaction/iteration can organize the graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection.
This graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection can also be organized by being optimized for problem-solving intents, so a set of graphs of problem/solution types connectible with these graphs is useful to apply as an additional graph to integrate in this set.
Similar graphs like 'interactions of definitions/requirements' and 'interactions of definitions/intents' can be organized by default as they will look similar, or can be organized by being optimized for position so similar graphs are in similar positions in each graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection, or these similarities can be applied as local axes of the graph of graphs, or similar graphs can have globally similar positions in the graph of graphs like a central position.

For example, a graph that is useful for a problem-solving intent has the meaning of being "probably useful for similar problem-solving intents or input/output intents of that problem-solving intent".
So the problem-solving intent structures (implemented as local connections or layers) connect to another layer of meaning, which has its own set of graphs like the intent meaning graph and the problem type meaning graph

A concept-function-intent graph is similar in usefulness to a concept-function-similarity graph, where the intent graph organizes the graph by usefulness for similar intents and the concept-function-similarity graph organizes the graph by similarity of function, which can be extended to organize the graph by stability to organize functions that have similar inputs/outputs or relevance, rather than just grouping similar functions which can have volatility in inputs/outputs or relevance.
The graph of similarities (similar function inputs/outputs, similar function structures, similar function intents) and the concepts these graph similarities implement (function relevance stability or volatility) is a useful relevant graph to identify.

This pairs context/intent to identify meaningful/relevant concepts of a function.

div.div:
The graph of input similarities/differences (function similarity, function-intent similarity) and the output similarities/differences (input/output volatility/stability) they create is a useful graph to identify when querying graph similarities to apply to create a graph that trivially identifies some similarity, which can be extended by context (function-intent similarity, given the context of a specific function type like cost functions, to create input/output stability, in relation to contextual variables like errors optimized for)
This is a useful extension of the function/structure graph or function/concept graph, organized by problem-solving intent.
This graph can repeat concept/function/structure/intent connections for different contexts, or context can be another organizing layer in addition to problem-solving intent. (Context, as in specific relevant system structures, can organize functions relevant to a context like creating cost functions, and then problem-solving intent can be a secondary organizing layer within that context like how cost functions can be used to implement problem-solving intents). Alternate variables than context/specificity like general solution metrics like accuracy/stability can be used to create alternate organizing layers (as in "identify the graph similarities that create the most stability across variable/function sets").
